# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fpga-hdl
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific integrated circuit** (**ASIC** /ˈeɪsɪk/) is an integrated circuit (IC) chip customized for a particular use, rather than intended for general-purpose use, such as a chip designed to run in a digital voice recorder or a high-efficiency video codec.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Application-specific standard product chips are intermediate between ASICs and industry standard integrated circuits like the 7400 series or the 4000 series.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASIC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, as MOS integrated circuit chips.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As feature sizes have shrunk and chip design tools improved over the years, the maximum complexity (and hence functionality) possible in an ASIC has grown from 5,000 logic gates to over 100 million.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Modern ASICs often include entire microprocessors, memory blocks including ROM, RAM, EEPROM, flash memory and other large building blocks.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such an ASIC is often termed a SoC (system-on-chip).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers of digital ASICs often use a hardware description language (HDL), such as Verilog or VHDL, to describe the functionality of ASICs.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) are the modern-day technology improvement on breadboards, meaning that they are not made to be application-specific as opposed to ASICs.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Programmable logic blocks and programmable interconnects allow the same FPGA to be used in many different applications.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For smaller designs or lower production volumes, FPGAs may be more cost-effective than an ASIC design, even in production.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The non-recurring engineering (NRE) cost of an ASIC can run into the millions of dollars.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Therefore, device manufacturers typically prefer FPGAs for prototyping and devices with low production volume and ASICs for very large production volumes where NRE costs can be amortized across many devices.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By 1967, Ferranti and Interdesign were manufacturing early bipolar gate arrays.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In 1967, Fairchild Semiconductor introduced the Micromatrix family of bipolar diode–transistor logic (DTL) and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) arrays.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology opened the door to the broad commercialization of gate arrays.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The first CMOS gate arrays were developed by Robert Lipp, in 1974 for International Microcircuits, Inc.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) standard-cell technology was introduced by Fairchild and Motorola, under the trade names Micromosaic and Polycell, in the 1970s.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This technology was later successfully commercialized by VLSI Technology (founded 1979) and LSI Logic (1981).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A successful commercial application of gate array circuitry was found in the low-end 8-bit ZX81 and ZX Spectrum personal computers, introduced in 1981 and 1982.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These were used by Sinclair Research (UK) essentially as a low-cost I/O solution aimed at handling the computer's graphics.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Customization occurred by varying a metal interconnect mask.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate arrays had complexities of up to a few thousand gates; this is now called mid-scale integration.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Later versions became more generalized, with different base dies customized by both metal and polysilicon layers.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some base dies also include random-access memory (RAM) elements.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1980s, a designer would choose an ASIC manufacturer and implement their design using the design tools available from the manufacturer.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While third-party design tools were available, there was not an effective link from the third-party design tools to the layout and actual semiconductor process performance characteristics of the various ASIC manufacturers.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Most designers used factory-specific tools to complete the implementation of their designs.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A solution to this problem, which also yielded a much higher density device, was the implementation of standard cells.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Every ASIC manufacturer could create functional blocks with known electrical characteristics, such as propagation delay, capacitance and inductance, that could also be represented in third-party tools.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is the utilization of these functional blocks to achieve very high gate density and good electrical performance.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is intermediate between § Gate-array and semi-custom design and § Full-custom design in terms of its non-recurring engineering and recurring component costs as well as performance and speed of development (including time to market).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, logic synthesis tools became available.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such tools could compile HDL descriptions into a gate-level netlist.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Register-transfer level (RTL) design**: The design team constructs a description of an ASIC to achieve these goals using a hardware description language.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This process is similar to writing a computer program in a high-level language.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Functional verification**: Suitability for purpose is verified by functional verification.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This may include such techniques as logic simulation through test benches, formal verification, emulation, or creating and evaluating an equivalent pure software model, as in Simics.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Each verification technique has advantages and disadvantages, and most often several methods are used together for ASIC verification.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Unlike most FPGAs, ASICs cannot be reprogrammed once fabricated and therefore ASIC designs that are not completely correct are much more costly, increasing the need for full test coverage.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Logic synthesis**: Logic synthesis transforms the RTL design into a large collection called of lower-level constructs called standard cells.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These constructs are taken from a standard-cell library consisting of pre-characterized collections of logic gates performing specific functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The standard cells are typically specific to the planned manufacturer of the ASIC.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The resulting collection of standard cells and the needed electrical connections between them is called a gate-level netlist.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Placement**: The gate-level netlist is next processed by a placement tool which places the standard cells onto a region of an integrated circuit die representing the final ASIC.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The placement tool attempts to find an optimized placement of the standard cells, subject to a variety of specified constraints.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Routing**: An electronics routing tool takes the physical placement of the standard cells and uses the netlist to create the electrical connections between them.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Since the search space is large, this process will produce a "sufficient" rather than "globally optimal" solution.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The output is a file which can be used to create a set of photomasks enabling a semiconductor fabrication facility, commonly called a "fab" or "foundry" to manufacture physical integrated circuits.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Placement and routing are closely interrelated and are collectively called place and route in electronics design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While Logic synthesis, Placement, and Routing are supported by electronic design automation tools, these stages require significant designer guidance and iteration.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers provide constraints derived from requirements engineering and RTL design, including timing requirements, floorplans, power budgets, and area restrictions.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Multiple tool iterations are typically necessary to meet performance, power, and area objectives, often requiring manual optimization and refinement that extends design cycle time considerably.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Sign-off**: Given the final layout, circuit extraction computes the parasitic resistances and capacitances.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the case of a digital circuit, this will then be further mapped into delay information from which the circuit performance can be estimated, usually by static timing analysis.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This, and other final tests such as design rule checking and power analysis collectively called signoff are intended to ensure that the device will function correctly over all extremes of the process, voltage and temperature.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] When this testing is complete the photomask information is released for chip fabrication.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These steps, implemented with a level of skill common in the industry, almost always produce a final device that correctly implements the original design, unless flaws are later introduced by the physical fabrication process.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The design steps also called design flow, are common to standard product design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The significant difference is that standard-cell design uses the manufacturer's cell libraries that have been used in potentially hundreds of other design implementations and therefore are of much lower risk than a full custom design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard cells produce a design density that is cost-effective, and they can also integrate IP cores and static random-access memory (SRAM) effectively, unlike gate arrays.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate array design is a manufacturing method in which diffused layers, each consisting of transistors and other active devices, are predefined and electronics wafers containing such devices are "held in stock" or unconnected prior to the metallization stage of the fabrication process.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The physical design process defines the interconnections of these layers for the final device.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For most ASIC manufacturers, this consists of between two and nine metal layers with each layer running perpendicular to the one below it.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Non-recurring engineering costs are much lower than full custom designs, as photolithographic masks are required only for the metal layers.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Production cycles are much shorter, as metallization is a comparatively quick process; thereby accelerating time to market.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate-array ASICs are always a compromise between rapid design and performance as mapping a given design onto what a manufacturer held as a stock wafer never gives 100% circuit utilization.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often difficulties in routing the interconnect require migration onto a larger array device with a consequent increase in the piece part price.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These difficulties are often a result of the layout EDA software used to develop the interconnect.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Pure, logic-only gate-array design is rarely implemented by circuit designers today, having been almost entirely replaced by field-programmable devices.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The most prominent of such devices are field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which can be programmed by the user and thus offer minimal tooling charges, non-recurring engineering, only marginally increased piece part cost, and comparable performance.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Today, gate arrays are evolving into structured ASICs that consist of a large IP core like a CPU, digital signal processor units, peripherals, standard interfaces, integrated memories, SRAM, and a block of reconfigurable, uncommitted logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In their frequent usages in the field, the terms "gate array" and "semi-custom" are synonymous when referring to ASICs.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Process engineers more commonly use the term "semi-custom", while "gate-array" is more commonly used by logic (or gate-level) designers.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, full-custom ASIC design defines all the photolithographic layers of the device.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Full-custom design is used for both ASIC design and for standard product design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The benefits of full-custom design include reduced area (and therefore recurring component cost), performance improvements, and also the ability to integrate analog components and other pre-designed—and thus fully verified—components, such as microprocessor cores, that form a system on a chip.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The disadvantages of full-custom design can include increased manufacturing and design time, increased non-recurring engineering costs, more complexity in the computer-aided design (CAD) and electronic design automation systems, and a much higher skill requirement on the part of the design team.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For digital-only designs, however, "standard-cell" cell libraries, together with modern CAD systems, can offer considerable performance/cost benefits with low risk.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Automated layout tools are quick and easy to use and also offer the possibility to "hand-tweak" or manually optimize any performance-limiting aspect of the design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is designed by using basic logic gates, circuits or layout specially for a design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is effectively the same definition as a gate array.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What distinguishes a structured ASIC from a gate array is that in a gate array, the predefined metal layers serve to make manufacturing turnaround faster.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In a structured ASIC, the use of predefined metallization is primarily to reduce cost of the mask sets as well as making the design cycle time significantly shorter.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, in a cell-based or gate-array design the user must often design power, clock, and test structures themselves.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, these are predefined in most structured ASICs and therefore can save time and expense for the designer compared to gate-array based designs.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Likewise, the design tools used for structured ASIC can be substantially lower cost and easier (faster) to use than cell-based tools, because they do not have to perform all the functions that cell-based tools do.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In some cases, the structured ASIC vendor requires customized tools for their device (e.g., custom physical synthesis) be used, also allowing for the design to be brought into manufacturing more quickly.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Cell libraries of logical primitives are usually provided by the device manufacturer as part of the service.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Although they will incur no additional cost, their release will be covered by the terms of a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) and they will be regarded as intellectual property by the manufacturer.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Usually, their physical design will be pre-defined so they could be termed "hard macros".
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What most engineers understand as "intellectual property" are IP cores, designs purchased from a third-party as sub-components of a larger ASIC.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] They may be provided in the form of a hardware description language (often termed a "soft macro"), or as a fully routed design that could be printed directly onto an ASIC's mask (often termed a "hard macro").
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Many organizations now sell such pre-designed cores – CPUs, Ethernet, USB or telephone interfaces – and larger organizations may have an entire department or division to produce cores for the rest of the organization.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The company ARM *only* sells IP cores, making it a fabless manufacturer.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Additionally, open-source hardware organizations such as OpenCores are collecting free IP cores, paralleling the open-source software movement in hardware design.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Soft macros are often process-independent (i.e. they can be fabricated on a wide range of manufacturing processes and different manufacturers).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Hard macros are process-limited and usually further design effort must be invested to migrate (port) to a different process or manufacturer.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some manufacturers and IC design houses offer multi-project wafer service (MPW) as a method of obtaining low cost prototypes.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often called shuttles, these MPWs, containing several designs, run at regular, scheduled intervals on a "cut and go" basis, usually with limited liability on the part of the manufacturer.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The contract involves delivery of bare dies or the assembly and packaging of a handful of devices.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The service usually involves the supply of a physical design database (i.e. masking information or pattern generation (PG) tape).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The manufacturer is often referred to as a "silicon foundry" due to the low involvement it has in the process.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific standard product** (**ASSP**) is an integrated circuit that implements a specific function that appeals to a wide market.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As opposed to ASICs that combine a collection of functions and are designed by or for one customer, ASSPs are available as off-the-shelf components.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASSPs are used in all industries, from automotive to communications.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, two ICs that might or might not be considered ASICs are a controller chip for a PC and a chip for a modem.
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Both of these examples are specific to an application (which is typical of an ASIC) but are sold to many different system vendors (which is typical of standard parts).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASICs such as these are sometimes called application-specific standard products (ASSPs).
[src:fpga-hdl/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Examples of ASSPs are encoding/decoding chip, Ethernet network interface controller chip and flash memory controller chip.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] A **field-programmable gate array** (**FPGA**) is a type of configurable integrated circuit that can be repeatedly programmed after manufacturing.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are a subset of logic devices referred to as programmable logic devices (PLDs).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] They consist of a grid-connected array of programmable logic blocks that can be configured "in the field" to interconnect with other logic blocks to perform various digital functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are often used in limited (low) quantity production of custom-made products, and in research and development, where the higher cost of individual FPGAs is not as important and where creating and manufacturing a custom circuit would not be feasible.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Other applications for FPGAs include the telecommunications, automotive, aerospace, and industrial sectors, which benefit from their flexibility, high signal processing speed, and parallel processing abilities.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA configuration is generally written using a hardware description language (HDL), e.g., VHDL, similar to the ones used for application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Circuit diagrams were formerly used to write the configuration.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The logic blocks of an FPGA can be configured to perform complex combinational functions, or act as simple logic gates like AND and XOR.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In most FPGAs, logic blocks also include memory elements, which may be simple flip-flops or more sophisticated blocks of memory.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Many FPGAs can be reprogrammed to implement different logic functions, allowing flexible reconfigurable computing as performed in computer software.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are also commonly used during the development of ASICs to speed up the simulation process.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The FPGA industry sprouted from programmable read-only memory (PROM) and programmable logic devices (PLDs).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] PROMs and PLDs both had the option of being programmed in batches in a factory or in the field (field-programmable).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera was founded in 1983 and delivered the industry's first reprogrammable logic device in 1984 – the EP300 – which featured a quartz window in the package that allowed users to shine an ultraviolet lamp on the die to erase the EPROM cells that held the device configuration.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx (now owned by AMD) produced the first commercially viable field-programmable gate array in 1985 – the XC2064.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The XC2064 had programmable gates and programmable interconnects between gates, the beginnings of a new technology and market.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The XC2064 had 64 configurable logic blocks (CLBs), with two three-input lookup tables (LUTs).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In 1987, the Naval Surface Warfare Center funded an experiment proposed by Steve Casselman to develop a computer that would implement 600,000 reprogrammable gates.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Casselman was successful and a patent related to the system was issued in 1992.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera and Xilinx continued unchallenged and quickly grew from 1985 to the mid-1990s when competitors sprouted up, eroding a significant portion of their market share.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] By 1993, Actel (later Microsemi, now Microchip) was serving about 18 percent of the market.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The 1990s were a period of rapid growth for FPGAs, both in circuit sophistication and the volume of production.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In the early 1990s, FPGAs were primarily used in telecommunications and networking.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] By the end of the decade, FPGAs found their way into consumer, automotive, and industrial applications.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] By 2013, Altera (31 percent), Xilinx (36 percent), and Actel (10 percent) together represented approximately 77 percent of the FPGA market.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Companies like Microsoft have started to use FPGAs to accelerate high-performance, computationally intensive systems (like the data centers that operate their Bing search engine), due to the performance per watt advantage FPGAs deliver.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Microsoft began using FPGAs to accelerate Bing in 2014, and in 2018 began deploying FPGAs across other data center workloads for their Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Since 2019, modern generations of FPGAs have been integrated with other architectures like AI engines to target workloads in the artificial intelligence domain.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The following timelines indicate progress in different aspects of FPGA design.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] A *design start* is a new custom design for implementation on an FPGA.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Contemporary FPGAs have ample logic gates and RAM blocks to implement complex digital computations.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs can be used to implement any logical function that an ASIC can perform.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The ability to update the functionality after shipping, partial re-configuration of a portion of the design and the low non-recurring engineering costs relative to an ASIC design (notwithstanding the generally higher unit cost), offer advantages for many applications.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] As FPGA designs employ very fast I/O rates and bidirectional data buses, it becomes a challenge to verify correct timing of valid data within setup time and hold time.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Floor planning helps resource allocation within FPGAs to meet these timing constraints.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs have analog features in addition to digital functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common analog feature is a programmable slew rate on each output pin.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] This allows the user to set low rates on lightly loaded pins that would otherwise ring or couple unacceptably, and to set higher rates on heavily loaded high-speed channels that would otherwise run too slowly.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Also common are quartz-crystal oscillator driver circuitry, on-chip RC oscillators, and phase-locked loops with embedded voltage-controlled oscillators used for clock generation and management as well as for high-speed serializer and deserializer (SERDES) transmit clocks and receiver clock recovery.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Fairly common are differential comparators on input pins designed to be connected to differential signaling channels.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] A few mixed-signal FPGAs have integrated peripheral analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) and digital-to-analog converters (DACs) with analog signal conditioning blocks, allowing them to operate as a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Such devices blur the line between an FPGA, which carries digital ones and zeros on its internal programmable interconnect fabric, and field-programmable analog array (FPAA), which carries analog values on its internal programmable interconnect fabric.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common FPGA architecture consists of an array of logic blocks called configurable logic blocks (CLBs) or logic array blocks (LABs) (depending on vendor), I/O pads, and routing channels.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Generally, all the routing channels have the same width (number of signals).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Multiple I/O pads may fit into the height of one row or the width of one column in the array.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] "An application circuit must be mapped into an FPGA with adequate resources.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] While the number of logic blocks and I/Os required is easily determined from the design, the number of routing channels needed may vary considerably even among designs with the same amount of logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, a crossbar switch requires much more routing than a systolic array with the same gate count.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Since unused routing channels increase the cost (and decrease the performance) of the FPGA without providing any benefit, FPGA manufacturers try to provide just enough channels so that most designs that will fit in terms of lookup tables (LUTs) and I/Os can be routed.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In general, a logic block consists of a few logical cells.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] A typical cell consists of a 4-input LUT, a full adder (FA) and a D-type flip-flop.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The LUT might be split into two 3-input LUTs.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In *normal mode* those are combined into a 4-input LUT through the first multiplexer (mux).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In *arithmetic* mode, their outputs are fed to the adder.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The selection of mode is programmed into the second mux.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The output can be either synchronous or asynchronous, depending on the programming of the third mux.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In practice, the entire adder or parts of it are stored as functions into the LUTs in order to save space.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Modern FPGA families expand upon the above capabilities to include higher-level functionality fixed in silicon.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Having these common functions embedded in the circuit reduces the area required and gives those functions increased performance compared to building them from logical primitives.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Examples of these include multipliers, generic DSP blocks, embedded processors, high-speed I/O logic and embedded memories.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Higher-end FPGAs can contain high-speed multi-gigabit transceivers and *hard IP cores* such as processor cores, Ethernet medium access control units, PCI or PCI Express controllers, and external memory controllers.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] These cores exist alongside the programmable fabric, but they are built out of transistors instead of LUTs so they have ASIC-level performance and power consumption without consuming a significant amount of fabric resources, leaving more of the fabric free for the application-specific logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The multi-gigabit transceivers also contain high-performance signal conditioning circuitry along with high-speed serializers and deserializers, components that cannot be built out of LUTs.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Higher-level physical layer (PHY) functionality such as line coding may or may not be implemented alongside the serializers and deserializers in hard logic, depending on the FPGA.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] An alternate approach to using hard macro processors is to make use of soft processor IP cores that are implemented within the FPGA logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Nios II, MicroBlaze and Mico32 are examples of popular softcore processors.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Many modern FPGAs are programmed at *run time*, which has led to the idea of reconfigurable computing or reconfigurable systems – CPUs that reconfigure themselves to suit the task at hand.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Additionally, new non-FPGA architectures are beginning to emerge.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Software-configurable microprocessors such as the Stretch S5000 adopt a hybrid approach by providing an array of processor cores and FPGA-like programmable cores on the same chip.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2012 the coarse-grained architectural approach was taken a step further by combining the logic blocks and interconnects of traditional FPGAs with embedded microprocessors and related peripherals to form a complete system on a programmable chip.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Examples of such hybrid technologies can be found in the Xilinx Zynq-7000 all programmable SoC, which includes a 1.0 GHz dual-core ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore processor embedded within the FPGA's logic fabric, or in the Altera Arria V FPGA, which includes an 800 MHz dual-core ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The Atmel FPSLIC is another such device, which uses an AVR processor in combination with Atmel's programmable logic architecture.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The Microsemi SmartFusion devices incorporate an ARM Cortex-M3 hard processor core (with up to 512 kB of flash and 64 kB of RAM) and analog peripherals such as a multi-channel analog-to-digital converters and digital-to-analog converters in their flash memory-based FPGA fabric.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Most of the logic inside of an FPGA is synchronous circuitry that requires a clock signal.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs contain dedicated global and regional routing networks for clock and reset, typically implemented as an H tree, so they can be delivered with minimal skew.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs may contain analog phase-locked loop or delay-locked loop components to synthesize new clock frequencies and manage jitter.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Complex designs can use multiple clocks with different frequency and phase relationships, each forming separate clock domains.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] These clock signals can be generated locally by an oscillator or they can be recovered from a data stream.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Care must be taken when building clock domain crossing circuitry to avoid metastability.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs contain dual port RAM blocks that are capable of working with different clocks, aiding in the construction of building FIFOs and dual port buffers that bridge clock domains.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] To shrink the size and power consumption of FPGAs, vendors such as Tabula and Xilinx have introduced 3D or stacked architectures.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Following the introduction of its 28 nm 7-series FPGAs, Xilinx said that several of the highest-density parts in those FPGA product lines will be constructed using multiple dies in one package, employing technology developed for 3D construction and stacked-die assemblies.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx's approach stacks several (three or four) active FPGA dies side by side on a silicon interposer – a single piece of silicon that carries passive interconnect.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The multi-die construction also allows different parts of the FPGA to be created with different process technologies, as the process requirements are different between the FPGA fabric itself and the very high speed 28 Gbit/s serial transceivers.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA built in this way is called a *heterogeneous FPGA*.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera's heterogeneous approach involves using a single monolithic FPGA die and connecting other dies and technologies to the FPGA using Intel's embedded multi-die interconnect bridge (EMIB) technology.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] To define the behavior of the FPGA, the user provides a design in a hardware description language (HDL) or as a schematic design.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The HDL form is more suited to work with large structures because it's possible to specify high-level functional behavior rather than drawing every piece by hand.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] However, schematic entry can allow for easier visualization of a design and its component modules.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Using an electronic design automation tool, a technology-mapped netlist is generated.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The netlist can then be fit to the actual FPGA architecture using a process called *place and route*, usually performed by the FPGA company's proprietary place-and-route software.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The user will validate the results using timing analysis, simulation, and other verification and validation techniques.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Once the design and validation process is complete, the binary file generated, typically using the FPGA vendor's proprietary software, is used to (re-)configure the FPGA.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] This file is transferred to the FPGA via a serial interface (JTAG) or to an external memory device such as an EEPROM.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common HDLs are VHDL and Verilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] National Instruments' LabVIEW graphical programming language (sometimes referred to as *G*) has an FPGA add-in module available to target and program FPGA hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Verilog was created to simplify the process, making HDL more robust and flexible.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Verilog has a C-like syntax, unlike VHDL which is based on Ada.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] To simplify the design of complex systems in FPGAs, there exist libraries of predefined complex functions and circuits that have been tested and optimized to speed up the design process.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] These predefined circuits are commonly called *intellectual property (IP) cores*, and are available from FPGA vendors and third-party IP suppliers.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] They are rarely free, and typically released under proprietary licenses.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Other predefined circuits are available from developer communities such as OpenCores (typically released under free and open source licenses such as the GPL, BSD or similar license).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Such designs are known as open-source hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In a typical design flow, an FPGA application developer will simulate the design at multiple stages throughout the design process.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Initially, the RTL description in VHDL or Verilog is simulated by creating test benches to simulate the system and observe results.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Then, after the synthesis engine has mapped the design to a netlist, the netlist is translated to a gate-level description where simulation is repeated to confirm the synthesis proceeded without errors.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Finally, the design is laid out in the FPGA at which point propagation delay values can be back-annotated onto the netlist, and the simulation can be run again with these values.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] More recently, OpenCL (Open Computing Language) is being used by programmers to take advantage of the performance and power efficiencies that FPGAs provide.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] OpenCL allows programmers to develop code in the C programming language.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] For further information, see high-level synthesis and C to HDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Most FPGAs rely on an SRAM-based approach to be programmed.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] These FPGAs are in-system programmable and re-programmable, but require external boot devices.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, flash memory or EEPROM devices may load contents into internal SRAM that controls routing and logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2016, long-time industry rivals Xilinx (now part of AMD) and Altera were the FPGA market leaders.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] At that time, they controlled nearly 90 percent of the market.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Both Xilinx and Altera provide proprietary electronic design automation software for Windows and Linux (ISE/Vivado and Quartus) which enables engineers to design, analyze, simulate, and synthesize (compile) their designs.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In March 2010, Tabula announced their FPGA technology that uses time-multiplexed logic and interconnect that claims potential cost savings for high-density applications.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] On March 24, 2015, Tabula officially shut down.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] On June 1, 2015, Intel announced it would acquire Altera for approximately US$16.7 billion and completed the acquisition on December 30, 2015.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] On October 27, 2020, AMD announced it would acquire Xilinx and completed the acquisition valued at about US$50 billion in February 2022.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In February 2024 Altera became independent of Intel again.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA can be used to solve any problem that is computable.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs can be used to implement a soft microprocessor, such as the Xilinx MicroBlaze or Altera Nios II.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] But their advantage lies in that they are significantly faster for some applications because of their parallel nature and optimality in terms of the number of gates used for certain processes.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs were originally introduced as competitors to complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) to implement glue logic for printed circuit boards.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] As their size, capabilities, and speed increased, FPGAs took over additional functions to the point where some are now marketed as full systems on chips (SoCs).
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Particularly with the introduction of dedicated multipliers into FPGA architectures in the late 1990s, applications that had traditionally been the sole reserve of digital signal processors (DSPs) began to use FPGAs instead.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The evolution of FPGAs has motivated an increase in the use of these devices, whose architecture allows the development of hardware solutions optimized for complex tasks, such as 3D MRI image segmentation, 3D discrete wavelet transform, tomographic image reconstruction, or PET/MRI systems.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The developed solutions can perform intensive computation tasks with parallel processing, are dynamically reprogrammable, and have a low cost, all while meeting the hard real-time requirements associated with medical imaging.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Another trend in the use of FPGAs is hardware acceleration, where one can use the FPGA to accelerate certain parts of an algorithm and share part of the computation between the FPGA and a general-purpose processor.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The search engine Bing is noted for adopting FPGA acceleration for its search algorithm in 2014.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] As of 2018, FPGAs are seeing increased use as AI accelerators including Microsoft's Project Catapult and for accelerating artificial neural networks for machine learning applications.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Originally, FPGAs were reserved for specific vertical applications where the volume of production is small.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] For these low-volume applications, the premium that companies pay in hardware cost per unit for a programmable chip is more affordable than the development resources spent on creating an ASIC.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Often a custom-made chip would be cheaper if made in larger quantities, but FPGAs may be chosen to quickly bring a product to market.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] By 2017, new cost and performance dynamics broadened the range of viable applications.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs play a crucial role in modern military communications, especially in systems like the Joint Tactical Radio System (JTRS) and in devices from companies such as Thales and Harris Corporation.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Their flexibility and programmability make them ideal for military communications, offering customizable and secure signal processing.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In the JTRS, used by the US military, FPGAs provide adaptability and real-time processing, crucial for meeting various communication standards and encryption methods.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Concerning hardware security, FPGAs have both advantages and disadvantages as compared to ASICs or secure microprocessors.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs' flexibility makes malicious modifications during fabrication a lower risk.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Previously, for many FPGAs, the design bitstream was exposed while the FPGA loads it from external memory, typically during powerup.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] All major FPGA vendors now offer a spectrum of security solutions to designers, such as bitstream encryption and authentication.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, Altera and Xilinx offer AES encryption (up to 256-bit) for bitstreams stored in an external flash memory.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Physical unclonable functions (PUFs) are integrated circuits that have their own unique signatures and can be used to secure FPGAs while taking up very little hardware space.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs that store their configuration internally in nonvolatile flash memory, such as Microsemi's ProAsic 3 or Lattice's XP2 programmable devices, do not expose the bitstream and do not need encryption.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Customers wanting a higher guarantee of tamper resistance can use write-once, antifuse FPGAs from vendors such as Microsemi.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] With its Stratix 10 FPGAs and SoCs, Altera introduced a Secure Device Manager and physical unclonable functions to provide high levels of protection against physical attacks.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2012, researchers Sergei Skorobogatov and Christopher Woods demonstrated that some FPGAs can be vulnerable to hostile intent.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2020, a critical vulnerability (named Starbleed) was discovered in all Xilinx 7 series FPGAs that rendered bitstream encryption useless.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx did not produce a hardware revision.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Ultrascale and later devices, already on the market at the time, were not affected.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Historically, FPGAs have been slower, less energy efficient and generally achieved less functionality than their fixed ASIC counterparts.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] A study from 2006 showed that designs implemented on FPGAs need on average 40 times as much area, draw 12 times as much dynamic power, and run at one third the speed of corresponding ASIC implementations.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Advantages of FPGAs include the ability to reprogram equipment in the field to fix bugs or make other improvements.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs have the capability of partial re-configuration that lets one portion of the device be re-programmed while other portions continue running.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Other advantages may include shorter time to market and lower non-recurring engineering costs.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Vendors can also take a middle road via FPGA prototyping: developing their prototype hardware on FPGAs, but manufacturing their final version as an ASIC after the design has been committed.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] This is often also the case with new processor designs.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] The primary differences between CPLDs and FPGAs are architectural.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] A CPLD has a comparatively restrictive structure consisting of one or more programmable sum-of-products logic arrays feeding a relatively small number of clocked registers.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] As a result, CPLDs are less flexible but have the advantage of more predictable propagation delay.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGA architectures, on the other hand, are dominated by interconnect.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] This makes them far more flexible but also far more complex to design for, or at least requiring more complex electronic design automation (EDA) software.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Another distinction between FPGAs and CPLDs is one of size, as FPGAs are usually much larger in terms of resources than CPLDs.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Typically only FPGAs contain more complex embedded functions such as adders, multipliers, memory, and serializer/deserializers.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Another common distinction is that CPLDs contain embedded flash memory to store their configuration, while FPGAs typically store their configuration in SRAM and require external non-volatile memory to initialize it on powerup.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] When a design requires simple instant-on, CPLDs are generally preferred.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] Sometimes both CPLDs and FPGAs are used in a single system design.
[src:fpga-hdl/field-programmable-gate-array] In those designs, CPLDs generally perform glue logic functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In computer engineering, a **hardware description language** (**HDL**) is a specialized computer language used to describe the structure and behavior of electronic circuits, usually to design application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) and to program field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language enables a precise, formal description of an electronic circuit that allows for the automated analysis and simulation of the circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] It also allows for the synthesis of an HDL description into a netlist (a specification of physical electronic components and how they are connected together), which can then be placed and routed to produce the set of masks used to create an integrated circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language looks much like a programming language such as C or ALGOL; it is a textual description consisting of expressions, statements and control structures.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] One important difference between most programming languages and HDLs is that HDLs explicitly include the notion of time.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs form an integral part of electronic design automation (EDA) systems, especially for complex circuits, such as application-specific integrated circuits, microprocessors, and programmable logic devices.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs were created to implement register-transfer level abstraction, a model of the dataflow and timing of a circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Two major hardware description languages exist: VHDL and Verilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In them, three different types of description occur: *dataflow*, *behavioral*, and *structural*.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs are standard text-based expressions of the structure of electronic systems and their behaviour over time.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Like concurrent programming languages, HDL syntax and semantics include explicit notations for expressing concurrency.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, in contrast to most software programming languages, HDLs also include an explicit notion of time, which is a primary attribute of hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Languages whose only characteristic is to express circuit connectivity between a hierarchy of blocks are properly classified as netlist languages used in electric computer-aided design.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDL can be used to express designs in structural, behavioral or register-transfer-level architectures for the same circuit functionality; in the latter two cases the synthesizer decides the architecture and logic gate layout.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs are used to write executable specifications for hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] A program designed to implement the underlying semantics of the language statements and simulate the progress of time provides the hardware designer with the ability to model a piece of hardware before it is created physically.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] It is this executability that gives HDLs the illusion of being programming languages, when they are more precisely classified as specification languages or modeling languages.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Simulators capable of supporting discrete-event (digital) and continuous-time (analog) modeling exist, and HDLs targeted for each are available.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] It is certainly possible to represent hardware semantics using traditional programming languages such as C++, which operate on control flow semantics in contrast to dataflow, although to function as such, programs must be augmented with extensive and unwieldy class libraries.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Generally, however, software programming languages include no ability to express time explicitly, and thus cannot function as hardware description languages.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Before the debut of System Verilog in 2002, C++ integration with a logic simulator was one of the few ways to use object-oriented programming in hardware verification.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] System Verilog is the first major HDL to offer object-orientation and garbage collection.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Using the proper subset of hardware description language, a program called a synthesizer, or logic synthesis tool, can infer hardware logic operations from the language statements and produce an equivalent netlist of generic hardware primitives to implement the specified behaviour.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Synthesizers generally ignore the expression of any timing constructs in the text.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Digital logic synthesizers, for example, generally use clock edges as the way to time the circuit, ignoring any timing constructs.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The ability to have a synthesizable subset of the language does not itself make a hardware description language.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The first hardware description languages appeared in the late 1960s, looking like more traditional languages.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The first that had a lasting effect was described in 1971 in C.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Gordon Bell and Allen Newell's text *Computer Structures*.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] This text introduced the concept of register transfer level, first used in the ISP language to describe the behavior of the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-8.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The language became more widespread with the introduction of DEC's PDP-16 RT-Level Modules (RTMs) and a book describing their use.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] At least two implementations of the basic ISP language (ISPL and ISPS) followed.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] ISPS was well suited to describe relations between the inputs and the outputs of the design and was quickly adopted by commercial teams at DEC, and by several research teams in the US and among its allies in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The RTM products never succeeded commercially and DEC stopped marketing them in the mid-1980s, as new methods grew more popular, more so very-large-scale integration (VLSI).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Separate work done about 1979 at the University of Kaiserslautern produced a language named *KAiserslautern Register Transfer Language* (KARL), which included design calculus language features supporting VLSI chip floorplanning and structured hardware design.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] This work was also the basis of KARL's interactive graphic sister language ABL, whose name was an initialism for "a block diagram language".
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] ABL was implemented in the early 1980s by the Centro Studi e Laboratori Telecomunicazioni (CSELT) in Torino, Italy, producing the ABLED graphic VLSI design editor.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In the mid-1980s, a VLSI design framework was implemented around KARL and ABL by an international consortium funded by the Commission of the European Union.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] By the late 1970s, design using programmable logic devices (PLDs) became popular, although these designs were primarily limited to designing finite-state machines.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The work at Data General in 1980 used these same devices to design the Data General Eclipse MV/8000, and commercial need began to grow for a language that could map well to them.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] By 1983 Data I/O introduced ABEL to fill that need.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In 1985, as design shifted to VLSI, Gateway Design Automation introduced Verilog, and Intermetrics released the first completed version of the VHSIC Hardware Description Language (VHDL).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] VHDL was developed at the behest of the United States Department of Defense's Very High Speed Integrated Circuit Program (VHSIC), and was based on the Ada programming language, and on the experience gained with the earlier development of ISPS.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Initially, Verilog and VHDL were used to document and simulate circuit designs already captured and described in another form (such as schematic files).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDL simulation enabled designers to work at a higher level of abstraction than simulation at the schematic level, and thus increased design capacity from hundreds of transistors to thousands.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In 1986, with the support of the U.S Department of Defense, VHDL was sponsored as an IEEE standard (IEEE Std 1076), and the first IEEE-standardized version of VHDL, IEEE Std 1076-1987, was approved in December 1987.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Cadence Design Systems later acquired Gateway Design Automation for the rights to Verilog-XL, the HDL simulator that would become the de facto standard of Verilog simulators for the next decade.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The introduction of logic synthesis for HDLs pushed HDLs from the background into the foreground of digital design.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Synthesis tools compiled HDL source code files (written in a constrained format named RTL) into a manufacturable netlist description in terms of logic gates and transistors.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Writing synthesizable RTL files required practice and discipline on the part of the designer; compared to a traditional schematic layout, synthesized RTL netlists were almost always larger in area and slower in performance.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Within a few years, VHDL and Verilog emerged as the dominant HDLs in the electronics industry, while older and less capable HDLs gradually disappeared from use.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, VHDL and Verilog share many of the same limits, such as being unsuitable for analog or mixed-signal circuit simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Specialized HDLs (such as Confluence) were introduced with the explicit goal of fixing specific limits of Verilog and VHDL, though none were ever intended to replace them.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Over the years, much effort has been invested in improving HDLs.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The latest iteration of Verilog, formally named IEEE 1800-2005 SystemVerilog, introduces many new features (classes, random variables, and properties/assertions) to address the growing need for better test bench randomization, design hierarchy, and reuse.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] A future revision of VHDL is also in development, and is expected to match SystemVerilog's improvements.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] As a result of the efficiency gains realized using HDL, a majority of modern digital circuit design revolves around it.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Most designs begin as a set of requirements or a high-level architectural diagram.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Control and decision structures are often prototyped in flowchart applications, or entered in a editor.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The process of writing the HDL description is highly dependent on the nature of the circuit and the designer's preference for coding style.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The HDL is merely the 'capture language', often beginning with a high-level algorithmic description such as a C++ mathematical model.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Designers often use scripting languages such as Perl to automatically generate repetitive circuit structures in the HDL language.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Special text editors offer features for automatic indentation, syntax-dependent coloration, and macro-based expansion of the entity/architecture/signal declaration.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The HDL code then undergoes a code review, or auditing.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In preparation for synthesis, the HDL description is subject to an array of automated checkers.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The checkers report deviations from standardized code guidelines, identify potential ambiguous code constructs before they can cause misinterpretation, and check for common logical coding errors, such as floating ports or shorted outputs.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] This process aids in resolving errors before the code is synthesized.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In industry parlance, HDL design generally ends at the synthesis stage.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Once the synthesis tool has mapped the HDL description into a gate netlist, the netlist is passed off to the back-end stage.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Depending on the physical technology (FPGA, ASIC gate array, ASIC standard cell), HDLs may or may not play a significant role in the back-end flow.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In general, as the design flow progresses toward a physically realizable form, the design database becomes progressively more laden with technology-specific information, which cannot be stored in a generic HDL description.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Finally, an integrated circuit is manufactured or programmed for use.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Essential to HDL design is the ability to simulate HDL programs.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Simulation allows an HDL description of a design (called a model) to pass design verification, an important milestone that validates the design's intended function (specification) against the code implementation in the HDL description.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] It also permits architectural exploration.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] A designer can experiment with design choices by writing multiple variations of a base design, then comparing their behavior in simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Thus, simulation is critical for successful HDL design.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] To simulate an HDL model, a designer writes a top-level simulation environment (called a test bench).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] At minimum, a testbench contains an instantiation of the model (called the device under test or DUT), pin/signal declarations for the model's input/output (I/O), and a clock waveform.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The testbench code is event driven: a designer writes HDL statements to implement the (testbench-generated) reset-signal, to model interface transactions (such as a host–bus read/write), and to monitor the DUT's output.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] An HDL simulator — the program that executes the testbench — maintains the simulator clock, which is the master reference for all events in the testbench simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Events occur only at the instants dictated by the testbench HDL (such as a reset-toggle coded into the testbench), or in reaction (by the model) to stimulus and triggering events.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Modern HDL simulators have full-featured graphical user interfaces, complete with a suite of debug tools.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] These allow the user to stop and restart the simulation at any time, insert simulator breakpoints (independent of the HDL code), and monitor or modify any element in the HDL model hierarchy.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Modern simulators can also link the HDL environment to user-compiled libraries, through a defined PLI/VHPI interface.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Linking is system-dependent (x86, SPARC etc. running Windows/Linux/Solaris), as the HDL simulator and user libraries are compiled and linked outside the HDL environment.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Design verification is often the most time-consuming portion of the design process, due to the disconnect between a device's functional specification, the designer's interpretation of the specification, and the imprecision of the HDL language.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Most of the initial test/debug cycle is conducted in the HDL *simulator* environment, as the early stage of the design is subject to frequent and major circuit changes.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] An HDL description can also be prototyped and tested in hardware — programmable logic devices are often used for this purpose.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Hardware prototyping is comparatively more expensive than HDL simulation, but offers a real-world view of the design.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Prototyping is the best way to check interfacing against other hardware devices and hardware prototypes.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Even those running on slow FPGAs offer much shorter simulation times than pure HDL simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Historically, design verification was a laborious, repetitive loop of writing and running simulation test cases against the design under test.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] As chip designs have grown larger and more complex, the task of design verification has grown to the point where it now dominates the schedule of a design team.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Looking for ways to improve design productivity, the electronic design automation industry developed the Property Specification Language.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In formal verification terms, a property is a factual statement about the expected or assumed behavior of another object.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Ideally, for a given HDL description, a property or properties can be proven true or false using formal mathematical methods.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In practical terms, many properties cannot be proven because they occupy an unbounded solution space.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, if provided a set of operating assumptions or constraints, a property checker can prove (or disprove) certain properties by narrowing the solution space.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The assertions do not model circuit activity, but capture and document the designer's intent in the HDL code.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In a simulation environment, the simulator evaluates all specified assertions, reporting the location and severity of any violations.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In a synthesis environment, the synthesis tool usually operates with the policy of halting synthesis upon any violation.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Assertion based verification is still in its infancy, but is expected to become an integral part of the HDL design toolset.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] An HDL is grossly similar to a software programming language, but there are major differences.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Most programming languages are inherently procedural (single-threaded), with limited syntactical and semantic support to handle concurrency.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs, on the other hand, resemble concurrent programming languages in their ability to model multiple parallel processes (such as flip-flops and adders) that automatically execute independently of one another.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Any change to the process's input automatically triggers an update in the simulator's process stack.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Both programming languages and HDLs are processed by a compiler (often called a synthesizer in the HDL case), but with different goals.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] For HDLs, "compiling" refers to logic synthesis; the process of transforming the HDL code listing into a physically realizable gate netlist.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] On the other hand, a software compiler converts the source-code listing into a microprocessor-specific object code for execution on the target microprocessor.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] As HDLs and programming languages borrow concepts and features from each other, the boundary between them is becoming less distinct.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, pure HDLs are unsuitable for general purpose application software development, just as general-purpose programming languages are undesirable for modeling hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Yet as electronic systems grow increasingly complex, and reconfigurable systems become increasingly common, there is growing desire in the industry for a single language that can perform some tasks of both hardware design and software programming.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] SystemC is an example of such—embedded system hardware can be modeled as non-detailed architectural blocks (black boxes with modeled signal inputs and output drivers).
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The target application is written in C or C++ and natively compiled for the host-development system; in contrast to targeting the embedded CPU, which requires host-simulation of the embedded CPU or an emulated CPU.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The high level of abstraction of SystemC models is well suited to early architecture exploration, as architectural modifications can be easily evaluated with little concern for signal-level implementation issues.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, the threading model used in SystemC relies on shared memory, causing the language not to handle parallel execution or low-level models well.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] In their level of abstraction, HDLs have been compared to assembly languages.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] There are attempts to raise the abstraction level of hardware design in order to reduce the complexity of programming in HDLs, creating a sub-field called *high-level synthesis*.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Companies such as Cadence, Synopsys and Agility Design Solutions are promoting SystemC as a way to combine high-level languages with concurrency models to allow faster design cycles for field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) than is possible using traditional HDLs.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Approaches based on standard C or C++ (with libraries or other extensions allowing parallel programming) are found in the Catapult C tools from Mentor Graphics, and the Impulse C tools from Impulse Accelerated Technologies.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] A similar initiative from Intel is the use of Data Parallel C++, related to SYCL, as a high-level synthesis language.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] It is also possible to design hardware modules using MATLAB and Simulink using the MathWorks HDL Coder tool or DSP Builder for Intel FPGAs or Xilinx System Generator (XSG) from Xilinx.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] The two most widely used and well-supported HDL varieties used in industry are Verilog and VHDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Several projects exist for defining printed circuit board connectivity using language based, textual-entry methods.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] Among these, new approaches have emerged that focus on enhancing readability, reusability, and validation.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] These modern methodologies employ open-source design languages specifically tailored for electronics, adopting declarative markup to specify what circuits should achieve.
[src:fpga-hdl/hardware-description-language] This shift integrates software development principles into hardware design, streamlining the process and emphasizing automation, reuse, and validation.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] In computer engineering, **logic synthesis** is a process by which an abstract specification of desired circuit behavior, typically at register transfer level (RTL), is turned into a design implementation in terms of logic gates, typically by a computer program called a *synthesis tool*.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Common examples of this process include synthesis of designs specified in hardware description languages, including VHDL and Verilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Some synthesis tools generate bitstreams for programmable logic devices such as PALs or FPGAs, while others target the creation of ASICs.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Logic synthesis is one step in circuit design in the electronic design automation, the others are place and route and verification and validation.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The roots of logic synthesis can be traced to the treatment of logic by George Boole (1815 to 1864), in what is now termed Boolean algebra.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] In 1938, Claude Shannon showed that the two-valued Boolean algebra can describe the operation of switching circuits.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] In the early days, **logic design** involved manipulating the truth table representations as Karnaugh maps.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The Karnaugh map-based minimization of logic is guided by a set of rules on how entries in the maps can be combined.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] A human designer can typically only work with Karnaugh maps containing up to four to six variables.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The first step toward automation of logic minimization was the introduction of the Quine–McCluskey algorithm that could be implemented on a computer.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] This exact minimization technique presented the notion of prime implicants and minimum cost covers that would become the cornerstone of two-level minimization.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Nowadays, the much more efficient Espresso heuristic logic minimizer has become the standard tool for this operation.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Another area of early research was in state minimization and encoding of finite-state machines (FSMs), a task that was the bane of designers.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The applications for logic synthesis lay primarily in digital computer design.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Hence, IBM and Bell Labs played a pivotal role in the early automation of logic synthesis.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The evolution from discrete logic components to programmable logic arrays (PLAs) hastened the need for efficient two-level minimization, since minimizing terms in a two-level representation reduces the area in a PLA.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Two-level logic circuits are of limited importance in a very-large-scale integration (VLSI) design; most designs use multiple levels of logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Almost any circuit representation in RTL or Behavioural Description is a multi-level representation.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] An early system that was used to design multilevel circuits was LSS from IBM.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] It used local transformations to simplify logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Work on LSS and the Yorktown Silicon Compiler spurred rapid research progress in logic synthesis in the 1980s.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Several universities contributed by making their research available to the public, most notably SIS from University of California, Berkeley, RASP from University of California, Los Angeles and BOLD from University of Colorado, Boulder.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Within a decade, the technology migrated to commercial logic synthesis products offered by electronic design automation companies.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The leading developers and providers of logic synthesis software packages are Synopsys, Cadence, and Siemens.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Their synthesis tools are Synopsys Design Compiler, Cadence First Encounter and Siemens Precision RTL.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Logic operations usually consist of Boolean AND, OR, XOR and NAND operations, and are the most basic forms of operations in an electronic circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Arithmetic operations are usually implemented with the use of logic operators.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] With a goal of increasing designer productivity, research efforts on the synthesis of circuits specified at the behavioral level have led to the emergence of commercial solutions in 2004, which are used for complex ASIC and FPGA design.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] These tools automatically synthesize circuits specified using high-level languages, like ANSI C/C++ or SystemC, to a register transfer level (RTL) specification, which can be used as input to a gate-level logic synthesis flow.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Typical practical implementations of a logic function utilize a multi-level network of logic elements.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Starting from an RTL description of a design, the synthesis tool constructs a corresponding multilevel Boolean network.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Next, this network is optimized using several technology-independent techniques before technology-dependent optimizations are performed.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The typical cost function during technology-independent optimizations is total literal count of the factored representation of the logic function (which correlates quite well with circuit area).
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Finally, technology-dependent optimization transforms the technology-independent circuit into a network of gates in a given technology.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] The simple cost estimates are replaced by more concrete, implementation-driven estimates during and after technology mapping.
[src:fpga-hdl/logic-synthesis] Mapping is constrained by factors such as the available gates (logic functions) in the technology library, the drive sizes for each gate, and the delay, power, and area characteristics of each gate.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In computer science, a **lookup table** (**LUT**) is an array that replaces runtime computation of a mathematical function with a simpler array indexing operation, in a process termed as ***direct addressing***.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The savings in processing time can be significant, because retrieving a value from memory is often faster than carrying out an "expensive" computation or input/output operation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The tables may be precalculated and stored in static program storage, calculated (or "pre-fetched") as part of a program's initialization phase (*memoization*), or even stored in hardware in application-specific platforms.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Lookup tables are also used extensively to validate input values by matching against a list of valid (or invalid) items in an array and, in some programming languages, may include pointer functions (or offsets to labels) to process the matching input.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] FPGAs also make extensive use of reconfigurable, hardware-implemented, lookup tables to provide programmable hardware functionality.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] LUTs differ from hash tables in that, to retrieve a value v with key k , a hash table would store the value v in the slot $h(k)$ where h is a hash function i.e. k is used to compute the slot, while in the case of LUT, the value v is stored in slot k , thus directly addressable.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Before the advent of computers, lookup tables of values were used to speed up hand calculations of complex functions, such as in trigonometry, logarithms, and statistical density functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In ancient (499 AD) India, Aryabhata created one of the first sine tables, which he encoded in a Sanskrit-letter-based number system.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Early in the history of computers, input/output operations were particularly slow – even in comparison to processor speeds of the time.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] It made sense to reduce expensive read operations by a form of manual caching by creating either static lookup tables (embedded in the program) or dynamic prefetched arrays to contain only the most commonly occurring data items.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Despite the introduction of systemwide caching that now automates this process, application level lookup tables can still improve performance for data items that rarely, if ever, change.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Lookup tables were one of the earliest functionalities implemented in computer spreadsheets, with the initial version of VisiCalc (1979) including a `LOOKUP` function among its original 20 functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Microsoft Excel includes multiple specialized lookup functions, with `VLOOKUP` for vertical lookup (as in a traditional lookup book), `HLOOKUP` for horizontal lookup, and (since 2019) `XLOOKUP` for outputting multiple output columns at once.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Although the performance of an LUT is a guaranteed $O(1)$ for a lookup operation, no two entities or values can have the same key k .
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] When the size of universe U —where the keys are drawn—is large, it might be impractical or impossible to be stored in memory.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] For a trivial hash function lookup, the unsigned raw data value is used *directly* as an index to a one-dimensional table to extract a result.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] For small ranges, this can be amongst the fastest lookup, even exceeding binary search speed with zero branches and executing in constant time.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] One discrete problem that is expensive to solve on many computers is that of counting the number of bits that are set to 1 in a (binary) number, sometimes called the *population function*.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] For example, the decimal number "37" is "00100101" in binary, so it contains three bits that are set to binary "1".
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The above implementation requires 32 operations for an evaluation of a 32-bit value, which can potentially take several clock cycles due to branching.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] It can be "unrolled" into a lookup table which in turn uses trivial hash function for better performance.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The bits array, *bits_set* with 256 entries is constructed by giving the number of one bits set in each possible byte value (e.g.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Sum of ones in each byte of the integer can be calculated through trivial hash function lookup on each byte; thus, effectively avoiding branches resulting in considerable improvement in performance.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In data analysis applications, such as image processing, a lookup table (LUT) can be used to transform the input data into a more desirable output format.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] For example, a grayscale picture of the planet Saturn could be transformed into a color image to emphasize the differences in its rings.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In image processing, lookup tables are often called **LUT**s (or 3DLUT), and give an output value for each of a range of index values.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] One common LUT, called the *colormap* or *palette*, is used to determine the colors and intensity values with which a particular image will be displayed.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In computed tomography, "windowing" refers to a related concept for determining how to display the intensity of measured radiation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] A classic example of reducing run-time computations using lookup tables is to obtain the result of a trigonometry calculation, such as the sine of a value.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Calculating trigonometric functions can substantially slow a computing application.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The same application can finish much sooner when it first precalculates the sine of a number of values, for example for each whole number of degrees (The table can be defined as static variables at compile time, reducing repeated run time costs).
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] When the program requires the sine of a value, it can use the lookup table to retrieve the closest sine value from a memory address, and may also interpolate to the sine of the desired value, instead of calculating by mathematical formula.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Lookup tables can thus be used by mathematics coprocessors in computer systems.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] An error in a lookup table was responsible for Intel's infamous floating-point divide bug.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Functions of a single variable (such as sine and cosine) may be implemented by a simple array.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Functions involving two or more variables require multidimensional array indexing techniques.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The latter case may thus employ a two-dimensional array of **power[x][y]** to replace a function to calculate **xy** for a limited range of x and y values.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Functions that have more than one result may be implemented with lookup tables that are arrays of structures.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] As mentioned, there are intermediate solutions that use tables in combination with a small amount of computation, often using interpolation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Pre-calculation combined with interpolation can produce higher accuracy for values that fall between two precomputed values.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] This technique requires slightly more time to be performed but can greatly enhance accuracy in applications that require it.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Depending on the values being precomputed, precomputation with interpolation can also be used to shrink the lookup table size while maintaining accuracy.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] While often effective, employing a lookup table may nevertheless result in a severe penalty if the computation that the LUT replaces is relatively simple.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Memory retrieval time and the complexity of memory requirements can increase application operation time and system complexity relative to what would be required by straight formula computation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The possibility of polluting the cache may also become a problem.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Table accesses for large tables will almost certainly cause a cache miss.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] This phenomenon is increasingly becoming an issue as processors outpace memory.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] A similar issue appears in rematerialization, a compiler optimization.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In some environments, such as the Java programming language, table lookups can be even more expensive due to mandatory bounds-checking involving an additional comparison and branch for each lookup.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] There are two fundamental limitations on when it is possible to construct a lookup table for a required operation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] One is the amount of memory that is available: one cannot construct a lookup table larger than the space available for the table, although it is possible to construct disk-based lookup tables at the expense of lookup time.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] The other is the time required to compute the table values in the first instance; although this usually needs to be done only once, if it takes a prohibitively long time, it may make the use of a lookup table an inappropriate solution.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] As previously stated however, tables can be statically defined in many cases.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Most computers only perform basic arithmetic operations and cannot directly calculate the sine of a given value.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] However, this can be expensive to compute, especially on slow processors, and there are many applications, particularly in traditional computer graphics, that need to compute many thousands of sine values every second.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] A common solution is to initially compute the sine of many evenly distributed values, and then to find the sine of *x* we choose the sine of the value closest to *x* through array indexing operation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] This will be close to the correct value because sine is a continuous function with a bounded rate of change.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Unfortunately, the table requires quite a bit of space: if IEEE double-precision floating-point numbers are used, over 16,000 bytes would be required.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] We can use fewer samples, but then our precision will significantly worsen.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] One good solution is linear interpolation, which draws a line between the two points in the table on either side of the value and locates the answer on that line.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] This is still quick to compute, and much more accurate for smooth functions such as the sine function.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Linear interpolation provides for an interpolated function that is continuous, but will not, in general, have continuous derivatives.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] For smoother interpolation of table lookup that is continuous **and** has continuous first derivative, one should use the cubic Hermite spline.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] When using interpolation, the size of the lookup table can be reduced by using *nonuniform sampling*, which means that where the function is close to straight, we use few sample points, while where it changes value quickly we use more sample points to keep the approximation close to the real curve.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] For more information, see interpolation.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] Storage caches (including disk caches for files, or processor caches for either code or data) work also like a lookup table.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] A single (fast) lookup is performed to read the tag in the lookup table at the index specified by the lowest bits of the desired external storage address, and to determine if the memory address is hit by the cache.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] When a hit is found, no access to external memory is needed (except for write operations, where the cached value may need to be updated asynchronously to the slower memory after some time, or if the position in the cache must be replaced to cache another address).
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In digital logic, a lookup table can be implemented with a multiplexer whose select lines are driven by the address signal and whose inputs are the values of the elements contained in the array.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] These values can either be hard-wired, as in an ASIC whose purpose is specific to a function, or provided by D latches which allow for configurable values.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] An *n*-bit LUT can encode any *n*-input Boolean function by storing the truth table of the function in the LUT.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] This is an efficient way of encoding Boolean logic functions, and LUTs with 4-6 bits of input are in fact the key component of modern field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which provide reconfigurable hardware logic capabilities.
[src:fpga-hdl/lookup-table] In some systems, polynomials may also be defined in place of lookup tables for these calculations.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:fpga-hdl/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In 2009, the Verilog standard (IEEE 1364-2005) was merged into the SystemVerilog standard, creating IEEE Standard 1800-2009.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Since then, Verilog has been officially part of the SystemVerilog language.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The current version is IEEE standard 1800-2023.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Hardware description languages such as Verilog use software-like syntax, but unlike software programming languages they model physical hardware, including concurrent operation, signal timing, and electrical behavior.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] There are two types of assignment operators; a blocking assignment (=), and a non-blocking (<=) assignment.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The non-blocking assignment allows designers to describe a state-machine update without needing to declare and use temporary storage variables.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Since these concepts are part of Verilog's language semantics, designers could quickly write descriptions of large circuits in a relatively compact and concise form.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] At the time of Verilog's introduction (1984), Verilog represented a tremendous productivity improvement for circuit designers who were already using graphical schematic capture software and specially written software programs to document and simulate electronic circuits.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The designers of Verilog wanted a language with syntax similar to the C programming language, which was already widely used in engineering software development.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Like C, Verilog is case-sensitive and has a basic preprocessor (though less sophisticated than that of ANSI C/C++).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Its control flow keywords (if/else, for, while, case, etc.) are equivalent, and its operator precedence is compatible with C.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Syntactic differences include: required bit-widths for variable declarations, demarcation of procedural blocks (Verilog uses begin/end instead of curly braces {}), and many other minor differences.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog requires that variables be given a definite size.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In C these sizes are inferred from the 'type' of the variable (for instance an integer type may be 32 bits).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A Verilog design consists of a hierarchy of modules.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Modules encapsulate *design hierarchy*, and communicate with other modules through a set of declared input, output, and bidirectional ports.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Internally, a module can contain any combination of the following: net/variable declarations (wire, reg, integer, etc.), concurrent and sequential statement blocks, and instances of other modules (sub-hierarchies).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Sequential statements are placed inside a begin/end block and executed in sequential order within the block.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] However, the blocks themselves are executed concurrently, making Verilog a dataflow language.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog's concept of 'wire' consists of both signal values (4-state: "1, 0, floating, undefined") and signal strengths (strong, weak, etc.).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This system allows abstract modeling of shared signal lines, where multiple sources drive a common net.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] When a wire has multiple drivers, the wire's (readable) value is resolved by a function of the source drivers and their strengths.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A subset of statements in the Verilog language are synthesizable.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog modules that conform to a synthesizable coding style, known as RTL (register-transfer level), can be physically realized by synthesis software.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Synthesis software algorithmically transforms the (abstract) Verilog source into a netlist, a logically equivalent description consisting only of elementary logic primitives (AND, OR, NOT, flip-flops, etc.) that are available in a specific FPGA or VLSI technology.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Further manipulations to the netlist ultimately lead to a circuit fabrication blueprint (such as a photo mask set for an ASIC or a bitstream file for an FPGA).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog was created by Prabhu Goel, Phil Moorby and Chi-Lai Huang between late 1983 and early 1984.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Chi-Lai Huang had earlier worked on a hardware description LALSD, a language developed by Professor S.Y.H.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The rights holder for this process, at the time proprietary, was "Automated Integrated Design Systems" (later renamed to Gateway Design Automation in 1985).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Gateway Design Automation was purchased by Cadence Design Systems in 1990.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Cadence now has full proprietary rights to Gateway's Verilog and the Verilog-XL, the HDL-simulator that would become the de facto standard (of Verilog logic simulators) for the next decade.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Originally, Verilog was only intended to describe and allow simulation; the automated synthesis of subsets of the language to physically realizable structures (gates etc.) was developed after the language had achieved widespread usage.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog is a portmanteau of the words "verification" and "logic".
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] With the increasing success of VHDL at the time, Cadence decided to make the language available for open standardization.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Cadence transferred Verilog into the public domain under the Open Verilog International (OVI) (now known as Accellera) organization.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog was later submitted to IEEE and became IEEE Standard 1364-1995, commonly referred to as Verilog-95.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In the same time frame Cadence initiated the creation of Verilog-A to put standards support behind its analog simulator Spectre.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog-A was never intended to be a standalone language and is a subset of Verilog-AMS which encompassed Verilog-95.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Extensions to Verilog-95 were submitted back to IEEE to cover the deficiencies that users had found in the original Verilog standard.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] These extensions became IEEE Standard 1364-2001 known as Verilog-2001.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog-2001 is a significant upgrade from Verilog-95.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] First, it adds explicit support for (2's complement) signed nets and variables.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Previously, code authors had to perform signed operations using awkward bit-level manipulations (for example, the carry-out bit of a simple 8-bit addition required an explicit description of the Boolean algebra to determine its correct value).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The same function under Verilog-2001 can be more succinctly described by one of the built-in operators: +, -, /, *, >>>.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A generate–endgenerate construct (similar to VHDL's generate–endgenerate) allows Verilog-2001 to control instance and statement instantiation through normal decision operators (case–if–else).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Using generate–endgenerate, Verilog-2001 can instantiate an array of instances, with control over the connectivity of the individual instances.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] File I/O has been improved by several new system tasks.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] And finally, a few syntax additions were introduced to improve code readability (e.g. always @*, named parameter override, C-style function/task/module header declaration).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Verilog-2001 is the version of Verilog supported by the majority of commercial EDA software packages.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Not to be confused with SystemVerilog, *Verilog 2005* (IEEE Standard 1364-2005) consists of minor corrections, spec clarifications, and a few new language features (such as the uwire keyword).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A separate part of the Verilog standard, Verilog-AMS, attempts to integrate analog and mixed signal modeling with traditional Verilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The advent of hardware verification languages such as OpenVera, and Verisity's e language encouraged the development of Superlog by Co-Design Automation Inc (acquired by Synopsys).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The foundations of Superlog and Vera were donated to Accellera, which later became the IEEE standard P1800-2005: SystemVerilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] SystemVerilog is a superset of Verilog-2005, with many new features and capabilities to aid design verification and design modeling.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] As of 2009, the SystemVerilog and Verilog language standards were merged into SystemVerilog 2009 (IEEE Standard 1800-2009).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The SystemVerilog standard was subsequently updated in 2012, 2017, and most recently in December 2023.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The `<=` operator in Verilog is another aspect of its being a hardware description language as opposed to a normal procedural language.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This is known as a "non-blocking" assignment.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Its action does not register until after the always block has executed.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This means that the order of the assignments is irrelevant and will produce the same result: flop1 and flop2 will swap values every clock.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The other assignment operator `=` is referred to as a blocking assignment.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] When `=` assignment is used, for the purposes of logic, the target variable is updated immediately.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In the above example, had the statements used the `=` blocking operator instead of `<=`, flop1 and flop2 would not have been swapped.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Instead, as in traditional programming, the compiler would understand to simply set flop1 equal to flop2 (and subsequently ignore the redundant logic to set flop2 equal to flop1).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The **always** clause above illustrates the other type of method of use, i.e. it executes whenever any of the entities in the list (the **b** or **e**) changes.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] When one of these changes, **a** is immediately assigned a new value, and due to the blocking assignment, *b* is assigned a new value afterward (taking into account the new value of **a**).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] After a delay of 5 time units, **c** is assigned the value of **b** and the value of **c ^ e** is tucked away in an invisible store.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Then after 6 more time units, **d** is assigned the value that was tucked away.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Signals that are driven from within a process (an initial or always block) must be of type **reg**.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Signals that are driven from outside a process must be of type **wire**.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The keyword **reg** does not necessarily imply a hardware register.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The definition of constants in Verilog supports the addition of a width parameter.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] There are several statements in Verilog that have no analog in real hardware, such as the $display command.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] However, the examples presented here are the classic (and limited) subset of the language that has a direct mapping to real gates.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The next interesting structure is a transparent latch; it will pass the input to the output when the gate signal is set for "pass-through", and captures the input and stores it upon transition of the gate signal to "hold".
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The output will remain stable regardless of the input signal while the gate is set to "hold".
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In the example below the "pass-through" level of the gate would be when the value of the if clause is true, i.e. gate = 1.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This is read "if gate is true, the din is fed to latch_out continuously." Once the if clause is false, the last value at latch_out will remain and is independent of the value of din.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The significant thing to notice in the example is the use of the non-blocking assignment.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A basic rule of thumb is to use **<=** when there is a **posedge** or **negedge** statement within the always clause.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A variant of the D-flop is one with an asynchronous reset; there is a convention that the reset state will be the first if clause within the statement.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The next variant is including both an asynchronous reset and asynchronous set condition; again the convention comes into play, i.e. the reset term is followed by the set term.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Note: If this model is used to model a Set/Reset flip flop then simulation errors can result.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Consider the following test sequence of events.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] 1) reset goes high 2) clk goes high 3) set goes high 4) clk goes high again 5) reset goes low followed by 6) set going low.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In this example the always @ statement would first execute when the rising edge of reset occurs which would place q to a value of 0.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The next time the always block executes would be the rising edge of clk which again would keep q at a value of 0.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The always block then executes when set goes high which because reset is high forces q to remain at 0.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This condition may or may not be correct depending on the actual flip flop.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] However, this is not the main problem with this model.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Notice that when reset goes low, that set is still high.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In a real flip flop this will cause the output to go to a 1.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] However, in this model it will not occur because the always block is triggered by rising edges of set and reset – not levels.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] A different approach may be necessary for set/reset flip flops.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The final basic variant is one that implements a D-flop with a mux feeding its input.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The mux has a d-input and feedback from the flop itself.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Note that there are no "initial" blocks mentioned in this description.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] There is a split between FPGA and ASIC synthesis tools on this structure.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] FPGA tools allow initial blocks where reg values are established instead of using a "reset" signal.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] ASIC synthesis tools don't support such a statement.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The reason is that an FPGA's initial state is something that is downloaded into the memory tables of the FPGA.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] An ASIC is an actual hardware implementation.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] There are two separate ways of declaring a Verilog process.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] These are the **always** and the **initial** keywords.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The **always** keyword indicates a free-running process.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The **initial** keyword indicates a process executes exactly once.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Both constructs begin execution at simulator time 0, and both execute until the end of the block.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Once an **always** block has reached its end, it is rescheduled (again).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] It is a common misconception to believe that an initial block will execute before an always block.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] In fact, it is better to think of the **initial**-block as a special-case of the **always**-block, one which terminates after it completes for the first time.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] These are the classic uses for these two keywords, but there are two significant additional uses.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The most common of these is an **always** keyword without the **@(...)** sensitivity list.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The **always** keyword acts similar to the C language construct **while(1) {..}** in the sense that it will execute forever.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The other interesting exception is the use of the **initial** keyword with the addition of the **forever** keyword.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The example below is functionally identical to the **always** example above.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The **fork/join** pair are used by Verilog to create parallel processes.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] All statements (or blocks) between a fork/join pair begin execution simultaneously upon execution flow hitting the **fork**.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Execution continues after the **join** upon completion of the longest running statement or block between the **fork** and **join**.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The way the above is written, it is possible to have either the sequences "ABC" or "BAC" print out.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The order of simulation between the first $write and the second $write depends on the simulator implementation, and may purposefully be randomized by the simulator.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This allows the simulation to contain both accidental race conditions as well as intentional non-deterministic behavior.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Notice that VHDL cannot dynamically spawn multiple processes like Verilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The order of execution is not always guaranteed within Verilog.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This can best be illustrated by a classic example.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Depending on the order of execution of the initial blocks, it could be zero and zero, or alternately zero and some other arbitrary uninitialized value.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The `$display` statement will always execute after both assignment blocks have completed, due to the #1 delay.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] Note: These operators are *not* shown in order of precedence.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The IEEE 1364 standard defines a four-valued logic with four states: 0, 1, Z (high impedance), and X (unknown logic value).
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] For the competing VHDL, a dedicated standard for multi-valued logic exists as IEEE 1164 with nine levels.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] System tasks are available to handle simple I/O and various design measurement functions during simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] All system tasks are prefixed with **$** to distinguish them from user tasks and functions.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] This section presents a short list of the most frequently used tasks.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The PLI provides a programmer with a mechanism to transfer control from Verilog to a program function written in C language.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] It is officially deprecated by IEEE Std 1364-2005 in favor of the newer Verilog Procedural Interface, which completely replaces the PLI.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] The PLI (now VPI) enables Verilog to cooperate with other programs written in the C language such as test harnesses, instruction set simulators of a microcontroller, debuggers, and so on.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] For example, it provides the C functions `tf_putlongp()` and `tf_getlongp()` which are used to write and read the 64-bit integer argument of the current Verilog task or function, respectively.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] For 32-bit integers, `tf_putp()` and `tf_getp()` are used.
[src:fpga-hdl/verilog] For information on Verilog simulators, see the list of Verilog simulators.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In 1983, VHDL was originally developed at the behest of the U.S.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Department of Defense in order to document the behavior of the ASIC that supplier companies were including in equipment.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The standard MIL-STD-454N in Requirement 64 in section 4.5.1 "ASIC documentation in VHDL" explicitly requires documentation of "Microelectronic Devices" in VHDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The idea of being able to simulate the ASICs from the information in this documentation was so obviously attractive that logic simulators were developed that could read the VHDL files.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The next step was the development of logic synthesis tools that read the VHDL and output a definition of the physical implementation of the circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Due to the Department of Defense requiring as much of the syntax as possible to be based on Ada, in order to avoid re-inventing concepts that had already been thoroughly tested in the development of Ada, VHDL borrows heavily from the Ada programming language in both concept and syntax.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The initial version of VHDL, designed to IEEE standard IEEE 1076–1987, included a wide range of data types, including numerical (integer and real), logical (bit and Boolean), character and time, plus arrays of `bit` called `bit_vector` and of `character` called string.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A problem not solved by this edition, however, was *multi-valued logic*, where a signal's drive strength (none, weak or strong) and unknown values are also considered.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] This required IEEE standard 1164, which defined the 9-value logic types: scalar `std_logic` and its vector version `std_logic_vector`.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Being a resolved subtype of its `std_Ulogic` parent type, `std_logic`-typed signals allow multiple driving for modeling bus structures, whereby the connected resolution function handles conflicting assignments adequately.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The updated IEEE 1076, in 1993, made the syntax more consistent, allowed more flexibility in naming, extended the `character` type to allow ISO-8859-1 printable characters, added the `xnor` operator, etc.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Minor changes in the standard (2000 and 2002) added the idea of protected types (similar to the concept of class in C++) and removed some restrictions from port mapping rules.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In addition to IEEE standard 1164, several child standards were introduced to extend functionality of the language.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] IEEE standard 1076.2 added better handling of real and complex data types.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] IEEE standard 1076.3 introduced signed and unsigned types to facilitate arithmetical operations on vectors.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] IEEE standard 1076.1 (known as VHDL-AMS) provided analog and mixed-signal circuit design extensions.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Some other standards support wider use of VHDL, notably **VITAL** (VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries) and microwave circuit design extensions.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In June 2006, the VHDL Technical Committee of Accellera (delegated by IEEE to work on the next update of the standard) approved so-called Draft 3.0 of VHDL-2006.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] While maintaining full compatibility with older versions, this proposed standard provides numerous extensions that make writing and managing VHDL code easier.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] These changes should improve quality of synthesizable VHDL code, make testbenches more flexible, and allow wider use of VHDL for system-level descriptions.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In February 2008, Accellera approved VHDL 4.0, also informally known as VHDL 2008, which addressed more than 90 issues discovered during the trial period for version 3.0 and includes enhanced generic types.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In 2008, Accellera released VHDL 4.0 to the IEEE for balloting for inclusion in IEEE 1076–2008.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The VHDL standard IEEE 1076-2008 was published in January 2009.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The IEEE Standard 1076 defines the VHSIC Hardware Description Language, or VHDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] It was originally developed under contract F33615-83-C-1003 from the United States Air Force awarded in 1983 to a team of Intermetrics, Inc. as language experts and prime contractor, Texas Instruments as chip design experts and IBM as computer-system design experts.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The language has undergone numerous revisions and has a variety of sub-standards associated with it that augment or extend it in important ways.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] IEEE Standard 1076 was and continues to be a milestone in the design of electronic systems.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] VHDL is generally used to write text models that describe a logic circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Such a model is processed by a synthesis program only if it is part of the logic design.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A simulation program is used to test the logic design using simulation models to represent the logic circuits that interface to the design.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] This collection of simulation models is commonly called a *testbench*.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A VHDL simulator is typically an event-driven simulator.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] This means that each transaction is added to an event queue for a specific scheduled time.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] For example, if a signal assignment should occur after 1 nanosecond, the event is added to the queue for time +1ns.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Zero delay is also allowed, but still needs to be scheduled: for these cases, delta delay is used, which represents an infinitely small time step.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The simulation alternates between two modes: statement execution, where triggered statements are evaluated, and event processing, where events in the queue are processed.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] VHDL has constructs to handle the parallelism inherent in hardware designs, but these constructs (*processes*) differ in syntax from the parallel constructs in Ada (*tasks*).
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Like Ada, VHDL is strongly typed and is not case sensitive.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In order to directly represent operations which are common in hardware, there are many features of VHDL which are not found in Ada, such as an extended set of Boolean operators including *nand* and *nor*.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] VHDL has file input and output capabilities, and can be used as a general-purpose language for text processing, but files are more commonly used by a simulation testbench for stimulus or verification data.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] There are some VHDL compilers that build executable binaries.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In this case, it might be possible to use VHDL to write a *testbench* to verify the functionality of the design using files on the host computer to define stimuli, to interact with the user, and to compare results with those expected.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] However, most designers leave this job to the simulator.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] It is relatively easy for an inexperienced developer to produce code that simulates successfully, but that cannot be synthesized into a real device, or is too large to be practical.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] One particular pitfall is the accidental production of transparent latches rather than D-type flip-flops as storage elements.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] One can design hardware in a VHDL IDE (for FPGA implementation, such as Xilinx ISE, Altera Quartus, Synopsys Synplify, or Mentor Graphics HDL Designer) to produce the RTL schematic of the desired circuit.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] After that, the generated schematic can be verified using simulation software, which shows the waveforms of inputs and outputs of the circuit after generating the appropriate testbench.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] To generate an appropriate testbench for a particular circuit or VHDL code, the inputs have to be defined correctly.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] For example, for clock input, a loop process or an iterative statement is required.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] When a VHDL model is translated into the gates and wires that are mapped onto a programmable logic device such as a CPLD or FPGA, then it is the actual hardware being configured, rather than the VHDL code being executed as if on some form of a processor chip.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The key advantage of VHDL, when used for systems design, is that it allows the behavior of the required system to be described (modeled) and verified (simulated) before synthesis tools translate the design into real hardware (gates and wires).
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Another benefit is that VHDL allows the description of a concurrent system.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] VHDL is a dataflow language in which every statement is considered for execution simultaneously, unlike procedural computing languages such as BASIC, C, and assembly language, where a sequence of statements is run sequentially, one instruction at a time.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Being created once, a calculation block can be used in many other projects.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] However, many formational and functional block parameters can be tuned (capacity parameters, memory size, element base, block composition and interconnection structure).
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Being created for one element base, a computing device project can be ported to another element base; for example, VLSI with various technologies.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A big advantage of VHDL compared to original Verilog is that VHDL has a full type system.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Designers can use the type system to write much more structured code (especially by declaring record types).
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In VHDL, a design consists at a minimum of an *entity* which describes the interface and an *architecture* which contains the actual implementation.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In addition, most designs import library modules.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Some designs also contain multiple architectures and *configurations*.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] (Notice that `RTL` stands for *Register transfer level* design.) While the example above may seem verbose to HDL beginners, many parts are either optional or need to be written only once.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Generally, simple functions like this are part of a larger behavioral module, instead of having a separate module for something so simple.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In addition, use of elements such as the `std_logic` type might at first seem to be an overkill.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] One could easily use the built-in `bit` type and avoid the library import in the beginning.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] However, using a form of many-valued logic, specifically 9-valued logic (`U`,`X`,`0`,`1`,`Z`,`W`,`H`,`L`,`-`), instead of simple bits (0,1) offers a very powerful simulation and debugging tool to the designer which currently does not exist in any other HDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In the examples that follow, one will see that VHDL code can be written in a very compact form.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] However, more experienced designers usually avoid these compact forms and use a more verbose coding style for the sake of readability and maintainability.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] VHDL is frequently used for two different goals: simulation of electronic designs and synthesis of such designs.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Synthesis is a process where a VHDL is compiled and mapped into an implementation technology such as an FPGA or an ASIC.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Not all constructs in VHDL are suitable for synthesis.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] For example, most constructs that explicitly deal with timing, such as `wait for 10 ns;` are not synthesizable despite being valid for simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] While different synthesis tools have different capabilities, there exists a common *synthesizable subset* of VHDL that defines what language constructs and idioms map into common hardware for many synthesis tools.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] IEEE 1076.6 defines a subset of the language that is considered the official synthesis subset.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] It is generally considered a best practice to write very idiomatic code for synthesis as results can be incorrect or suboptimal for non-standard constructs.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The multiplexer, or 'MUX' as it is usually called, is a simple construct very common in hardware design.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The example below demonstrates a simple two-to-one MUX, with inputs `A` and `B`, selector `S` and output `X`.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Note that there are many other ways to express the same MUX in VHDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A transparent latch is basically one bit of memory that is updated when an enable signal is raised.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Again, there are many other ways this can be expressed in VHDL.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The D-type flip-flop samples an incoming signal at the rising (or falling) edge of a clock.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] This example has an asynchronous, active-high reset and samples at the rising clock edge.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Another common way to write edge-triggered behavior in VHDL is with the 'event' signal attribute.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A single apostrophe has to be written between the signal name and the name of the attribute.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Which can be useful if not all signals (registers) driven by this process should be reset.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The following example is an up-counter with asynchronous reset, parallel load and configurable width.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] It demonstrates the use of the 'unsigned' type, type conversions between 'unsigned' and 'std_logic_vector' and VHDL *generics*.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The generics are very close to arguments or templates in other traditional programming languages like C++.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] More complex counters may add if/then/else statements within the `rising_edge(CLK) elsif` to add other functions, such as count enables, stopping or rolling over at some count value, and generating output signals like terminal count signals.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Care must be taken with the ordering and nesting of such controls if used together, in order to produce the desired priorities and minimize the number of logic levels needed.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] A large subset of VHDL cannot be translated into hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] This subset is known as the non-synthesizable or the simulation-only subset of VHDL and can only be used for prototyping, simulation and debugging.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] For example, the following code will generate a clock with a frequency of 50 MHz.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] It can, for example, be used to drive a clock input in a design during simulation.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] It is, however, a simulation-only construct and cannot be implemented in hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] In actual hardware, the clock is generated externally; it can be scaled down internally by user logic or dedicated hardware.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] The simulation-only constructs can be used to build complex waveforms in a very short time.
[src:fpga-hdl/vhdl] Such waveforms can be used, for example, as test vectors for a complex design or as a prototype of some synthesizer logic that will be implemented in the future.
